        <h2 class="text-center">The Flower Carrier by Diego Rivera</h2>
        
        <div class="col-md-8">
            <img class="flower-carrier" src="http://criticallegalthinking.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/The-Flower-Carrier-600x454.jpg" alt="The Flower Carrier">
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-4">
            <h3 class="text-center">Response</h3>
            <h4>
                The painting shows a man struggling to carry a large basket of 
                flowers on his back. A woman is helping him adjust the basket 
                so he can carry it. The painting makes a point on the common
                man of Mexico. It does not look like an easy life, the man is 
                on his hands and knees struggling. He relies on the assistance 
                of others to be able to do his job and survive. This is the 
                point Diego Rivera makes with his art. Rivera was the founder 
                of the communist party in Mexico. Sympathetic to the plight of 
                the common man, Rivera wanted to expose the struggles and 
                hardships the people of Mexico endure. While the party never 
                gained massive political power, this painting along with 
                Rivera’s other works are noted for representing a 
                counterculture movement in Mexico. Mexico is a country with 
                large wealth inequality, 27% live under the poverty line, and 
                some people wanted to take action. Rivera’s influence over the 
                culture of Mexico is notable, and this painting provides a good 
                example of his intentions. 
            </h4>
        </div>

