            <h3 class="text-center">Response</h3>
            <h4>
                The article gives a lot of historical background on the origins 
                of Mexico and why the culture is what it is today. There’s a 
                wealth of information, from language to ethnic relations to 
                food. Something I didn’t think about in my research was the 
                eating schedule in Mexico. They typically eat a large meal 
                between 2 and 4 pm and a dinner between 8 and 10. Different 
                than the American schedule, and it’s only one small piece of 
                culture that makes Mexico unique. Additionally, the article 
                talked of social relations and classes in Mexico. As alluded by 
                the previous artifacts I examined, I found there to be a large 
                wealth gap in Mexico. The top fifth of earners take home half 
                of the income of the country, while a quarter of the people live 
                below the poverty line. Gated communities are common among the 
                wealthy, and they will even hire armed guards for further 
                security. The wealthy enjoy their status and want to hold on to 
                it. Mexico also has its own unique holidays, one such is Dia de 
                los Muertos, or Day of the Dead. Around the same timeframe that 
                Halloween is celebrated in America, Dia de los Muertos is a 
                multiple day long celebration of the dead. They celebrate the 
                lives of family that have passed on with city-wide parties and 
                parades. Mexico has a culture ripe with customs and 
                celebrations, social inequality and political unrest, and 
                minute intricacies that make it unique compared to the rest of 
                the world. 
            </h4>
